Traditional Statistical Metric:

  • Discrimination ðŸ––: Modelâ€™s ability to separate between events and non-events (ROC Curve, AUROC, Sensitivity, Specificity, NPV, PPV, Lift etc).

  • Calibration âš–ï¸: Agreement between predicted probabilities and the observed outcomes (Calibration Curve, Calibration in the large, Calibration in the small etc).

  • ProblemðŸ›‘ These metrics are not directly informative to clinical value, nor to full decision analytic approaches.

  • SolutionðŸ‘Œ Decision Curve Analysis calculates a clinical â€œNet Benefitâ€ prediction models or diagnostic tests in comparison to default strategies of treating all or no patients.

Decision Tree

Decision Tree

Probability Threshold is derived from Equivalence between

\[EV_{Treat} = p(Disease) * U_{TP} + p(No Disease) * U_{FP}\]

\[EV_{NoTreat} = p(Disease) * U_{FN} + p(No Disease) * U_{TN}\]

Decision Tree

Probability Threshold is derived from Equivalence between

\[EV_{Treat} = EV_{{NoTreat}}\]

\[p(Disease) * U_{TP} + p(No Disease) * U_{FP} =p(Disease) * U_{FN} + p(No Disease) * U_{TN}\]

Decision Tree

Probability Threshold is derived from Equivalence between

\[EV_{Treat} = EV_{{NoTreat}}\]

\[p(Disease) * U_{TP} + (1-p(Disease)) * U_{FP} =p(Disease) * U_{FN} + (1-p(Disease)) * U_{TN}\]

Decision Tree

Probability Threshold is derived from Equivalence between

\[EV_{Treat} = EV_{{NoTreat}}\]

\[p(Disease) * (U_{TP} - U_{FN}) =(1-p(Disease)) * (U_{TN} - U_{FP})\]

Decision Tree

Probability Threshold is derived from Equivalence between

\[EV_{Treat} = EV_{{NoTreat}}\]

\[\frac{p(Disease)}{(1-p(Disease))} = \frac{(U_{TN} - U_{FP})}{(U_{TP} - U_{FN})}\]

Step 3 ðŸ‘£: Unit of Preference = Threshold Probability

Remember: almost always (specially in Health Care) -

Sensitivity does not have the same importance as Specificity and having 1 TP does not have the same clinical utility as having 1 FP.

A good example for a bad practice in evaluating performance of prediction model is the Youdenâ€™s J statistics:

\[{\displaystyle J={\frac {\green{\bf{TP}}}{{\green{\bf{TP}}}+{\red{\bf{FN}}}}}+{\frac {\green{\bf{TN}}}{{\green{\bf{TN}}}+{\red{\bf{FP}}}}}-1}\] Maximizing Youdenâ€™s J statistic might lead to a Probability Threshold that will do more harm than good, even if the prediction model is accurate!

Step 3 ðŸ‘£: Unit of Preference = Threshold Probability

I wouldnâ€™t give more than 4 antibiotics in order to help 1 infected patient.

If a patientâ€™s risk was above 20% I will give him antibiotics, otherwise I wonâ€™t.

The risk of 20% is an odds of 1:4, so in using a threshold probability of 20%, the doctor is telling us â€œmissing an infected patiant is 4 times worse than giving antibiotics to a healthy patient.â€

\[p_t = \frac{1}{1 + 4} = 0.2\] \[\frac{p_t}{1 - p_t} = \frac{0.2}{1 - 0.2} = \frac{1}{4}\]

I will be indifferent ðŸ˜

\[\begin{aligned}[t] {\text{Net Benefit}} &= {\frac{\text{1}}{\text{5}} - \frac{\text{4}}{\text{5}} * {\frac{1}{4}} = 0} \end{aligned}\]
